I blinked as the memories from 2014 returned to me. A waft of food cooked in the kitchen greeted my nose, and feet coming from in front of my cubicle clad in jeans and from dying in a battle between paying rent and getting new socks, reminded me that I'm indeed an adult who has most of her life figured out. “Right back at you,” I said idly, partly in jest. In 2014, I was very serious about my career; that is why I was multilingual, transnational, and didn’t bargain for nothing. But in 2014, another group, usually called the younger half, didn’t ask questions. Ask any woman on the road in 2014 what they want for the upcoming first month of summer, and almost everyone will say that “They want to be heard.” Whereas, in 2016, there have been events which made men realize that what they want has finally been heard; and instead of feeling like their rights have been levelled off even more, to men’s chagrin, their rights are in a state of limbo. That is, because most of the basis of their rights, such as whether or not your privacy has been violated under the law, is still in a state of limbo as well.  “Well, I do though,” I said. gave a look that I did not find to be the least bit funny. “Women don’t whine, we ask; and we ask to be heard. We ask to be treated with respect. We ask for people to treat us with civility and dignity. We ask to have the same chance and opportunities as men do.” She gave me a nod, and simply walked back to her desk.
No. We have not. ‘Thank you, Sir, for welcoming me as one of your equals and treating me not just as a woman, but as one of your team members.’ I said as I stood up. I walked out of the mall into my car.  That’s what I thought. “But, again,” I paused and took a slow breath. “We want the same chance as men,” I repeated, with a sad smile. 
