Every research study I have ever looked at in biological and social sciences ignores this issue, and if I try to include e.g. a quadratic term in a regression they conclude fully on the no-factor loading data, so I suspect there is a significant issue but I am the conversational equivalent of a primary school kid, so I figure I really need an answer from someone who is a real adult. But I really don't know why this isn't addressed in the curriculum?
Middle: There are two exceptions to the rule: the ""full factorial"" case and models with interactions between variables. In a full factorial design, the model includes all possible main effects and interactions between factors. In this case, each factor's coefficient can be interpreted as the main effect of that factor, independent of the other factors in the model.

In a model with interactions, the coefficient of one variable represents the effect of that variable when all other variables are set to zero. For example, consider a model that examines the effects of age, gender, and education level on income. If age is included as a main effect in the model along with an interaction term for age and gender, the age coefficient represents the effect of age on income for individuals with a high school education and no college degree.

The exceptions to this rule of no factor loadings on a regression can be used in practice to better understand the relationships between variables. For example, in a study examining the effects of smoking, exercise, and diet on heart disease, the inclusion of interaction terms in the regression model might reveal that the effects of smoking and exercise are modified by diet. This could have implications for public health policy and intervention efforts.",39.36202707290368,13.245843535810595
