 Titus-II

   Titus uses the functions written by the Gazelle in order to generate trade ships for added port functionality. Function is responsible for defining what kind of ship are being built or ordered by the players. I used a lot of functions and they are grouped in two categories: functions that produce information and ​​functions that produce preparation for start of building the ship - I wanted to keep things clear.

 

   For the first interface (Figure 7) an object of the type texture was created. My aim was to create this interface as close as possible look to the stereotypical Windows interface, so under the hood it will be simple text. That is why I used functions like renderings and drawlines. I tried to keep rubicons in the interface to the minimum. I've done it so that I can clearly understand what functions are being called and why. It was also beneficial given the fact that for the second interface there were only the ""button"" functions with no other added structures.

   In the next image is the second interface displaying the view of the texit itself. Here there aren't shown buttons, but as you can see I used a function that locates the player's docking point. That is the first function for production of the second interface, but I also wrote two functions that will track what the players rebuild are (CaptureDatabase) and track what teams there are (CapturaExperts). Now when the game stops and I used a special way to exit and start the game and save the data. I've done so that I avoid editing the players' universe and can see what players have and what they should do it.

 

   The last one is the player. Here you can see an artificial intelligence identification of an individual player (Titus officer). These are characters responsible for the operations. It shows the image of the player (our alien). The functions that are behind the interface on line no. 73-101 do calculations for player's data, and download them to a dialog box. Tables are hidden under lines 674-723, they serve as functions that centralize the data in the player's window. If you look at lines 472-537 you will see that data related to ships is mainly calculated here. From lines 538-681 you will see some pair data transferred to interface lines 675-723, there in the form of query string and clipped as text. Lines 724-738 show the variables used for the display of ships, if you look at lines 95-185 you will see that they show some ships that can be printed. Most data come from lines 250-517 and put into a list. From there they go into a dialogue box.",5.111002869449049,6.382105596517013
