Claudio Tedeschi was born on 5 May 1797 in Isola del Tronto near Fermo, Papal States. He was the son of Carlo Tedeschi and Giovanna Moriconi, and grew up in his father's orphanage in Aprilia, ancient Oraatium. He studied theology in the Pontifical Gregorian University of Rome, receiving a doctorate in 1813.

On 28 June 1814, the French, after the Napoleonic invasion of Italy, named Tedeschi, known in French as ""Claudio de Tedee"", governor of Vandœuvres, in the ""province artificielle"" of Switzerland. He was created a cardinal of the Holy Roman Church on 24 June 1824. He was ordained a priest on 4 February 1817.

He played a prominent role in the discussions of the Second Vatican Council, as a member of the committee of five cardinals who prepared the document ""Decree on the return of Christian liberty"" (18 November 1964). As governor of the Province, a ban on drinking in the Basilica was passed in 1798. However the number of sects, secret societies, liceal associations, and philosophic Societies, which doubled in 1806, remained high. The ""Decretum Benone"", issued in 1816, said that ""the strongholds and temples of superstition and heathenism were completely and irrevocably destroyed in Rome"". He also undertook measures against the Jesuits.

He died, at the age of 75, at the Generalate of Pontifical Colleges, Rome, on 6 March 1873.
