                                      Executive Summary
This report provides overall characterization and analysis of the U.S. health
insurance market and presents a framework for reviewing market results and
proposed solutions. The analysis serves as the intellectual underpinning for
the Commissioner of the National Association of Insurance Commissioners’
(NAIC) discussions and current review of the state regulatory oversight
approach to the health insurance industry. Key findings address four primary
topics:
– The existence of health insurance markets in the United States from
physician-driven group medical associations (governed by medical
licensing boards) through employer-based health-care benefit plan
sponsored by both voluntary and mandatory health-care benefit systems
(National Social Security–funded (Medicare) and state-funded (Med-
icaid) systems), including the voluntary benefits, such as health savings
accounts and health maintenance organizations;
– Trends over the past 40 years in the regulated portion of the health
insurance market: included in the analysis is data on the health-insurance
market in the United States, including enrollment, and to a certain degree
service availability, premia and spending and utilization; and
– Access to health-care coverage under the parity of the various types
of coverage schemes, and a detailed discussion on the barriers that some
special populations face in obtaining access to appropriate health-
care benefits, including the uninsured.
                                iii
The study employed a number of methods to develop characterizations
of each of the possible structures in the health care industry that are
part of this ecosystem. The NAIC reviewed and analyzed public data and
studies produced by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services,
through its Center for Consumer Information & Insurance Oversight
(Center) and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC);
regulatory forms and filings; peer-reviewed research literature; and
via public and private interviews with governmental regulatory agents,
a variety of industry stakeholders, and other interested parties.
The detailed structure of this report provides for the main body and
appendices of the report. Each section is identified by the structure
below.
– Part I – Executive Summary
– Introduction – Evolution of the Regulation of Health Insurance
– Health Insurance, Health Reform, and the Current Debate
– Health Insurance Market Structure and the Regulation of Health
  Insurance
– Framework for Health Insurance Reforms
– Measurements in the Health Insurance Context
– Definition",87.48231164814212,0.1275106617619376
