Find the greatest common divisor of 75 and 360. We can use the Euclidean algorithm to find the greatest common divisor (GCD) of 75 and 360.
\begin{align*}
\text{GCD}(75, 360) &= \text{GCD}(75, 360 - 4 \cdot 75) \\
&= \text{GCD}(75, 60) \\
&= \text{GCD}(60, 75 - 1 \cdot 60) \\
&= \text{GCD}(60, 15) \\
&= \text{GCD}(15, 60 - 4 \cdot 15) \\
&= \text{GCD}(15, 0) \\
&= \boxed{15}.
\end{align*}
The answer is: 15 
 John decides to take up illustration.  He draws and colors 10 pictures.  It takes him 2 hours to draw each picture and 30% less time to color each picture.  How long does he spend on all the pictures? John draws 10 pictures and it takes him 2 hours to draw each picture, so he spends a total of 10 * 2 = 20 hours drawing.
It takes him 30% less time to color each picture, so he spends 100% - 30% = 70% of the time to color each picture.
To find out how long it takes him to color each picture, we can calculate 70% of 2 hours: 0.70 * 2 = 1.4 hours.
So, he spends 1.4 hours to color each picture.
He draws 10 pictures, so he spends a total of 1.4 * 10 = 14 hours coloring.
Therefore, John spends a total of 20 + 14 = 34 hours on all the pictures.
#### 34
The answer is: 34 
