Nope. We are using numpy.random.choice to obtain a random permutation of the whole set. To be able to resample, we would have to split the original set into chunks and keep holdout chunks fixed. Following that, we train the model in batches and for each batch we shuffle the data. Whenever you call shuffle on the batches, you end up with another permutation and you could forget it until the next batch is loaded. So, all 10 batches with the same optimization algorithm would ideally use different shuffled batches.
Btw, if you operate with batches, I assume you are guaranteed to shuffle every epoch, aren't you?
But again, I have no idea why you need batches. If you really want self-righteous methods to do your epoch, you could drive them with a timeout based on tick().



