Practical Framework for Designing and Evaluating Agent-Based Models of Human and Nonhuman Social Behavior
 Tom R. Tyler 
New York University 
Abstract 
​
Agent-based models (ABMs) are characterized by mathematical model and algorithmic model.  The mathematical model includes mathematics, physics, sociology, and other formal mathematical components.  The algorithmic model reflects software, hardware, computing power, programming languages, and other formal computational components.  Together they comprise a ""whole system"" of theoretical components.  I propose a framework for designing and evaluating ABMs of human and nonhuman social behavior.  Designers should clarify the field, goal of research, research question, and the expected result, then design accordingly.  Evaluators should consider model in its algorithmic form.  Clarity about the expected result of the model is important for evaluating the degree of correspondence between the actual result of the simulation and this expected result.


Introduction
I use agent-based models (ABMs) to analyze social behavior.  There are three types of agent-based models.  The first type is statistical learning models.  The second type is individual difference models.  The third type is agent-based models. ABMs are characterized by their mathematical model and by their algorithmic model.  The mathematical model describes both individual behavior and how individuals interact.  The algorithmic model is software, hardware, computing power, programming language, and other computational formal components.  In this paper I compare these types of models and propose a framework for designing and evaluating ABMs.  At the moment there is little agreement about the optimal design of ABMs.  The idea of ABMs is that the researcher specifies rules that predict the type of behavior the researcher expects.  The unfolding of behavior follows these rules (if the model runs out of factors all possible runs of the model are exactly the same).  The extent to which the result includes the aspects of social behavior the researcher expects is a measure of the degree of correspondence between the expected result and the actual result.
Digital representation of social systems may occur when a computer is used to represent an Abstract  much larger version of a social system than could be expressed in terms of data and words.  In my simulations I have represented 15,258,032 agents and the interactions of all of these agents.  I propose 16 steps for the design of ABMs.  I also suggest there are four ways for evaluating ABMs.  In addition, I describe how to evaluate ABMs using a blueprint and inverse blueprint. ",42.497552848198815,28.256165316391993
