If one-half pound of peanuts plus one-third pound of walnuts for trail mix costs $2.10, and one-third pound of peanuts plus one-half pound of walnuts (not for trail mix) costs $1.80, what will be the cost of a one-pound bag of walnuts, if the cost of the additives for the trail mix is $0.17 per pound of trail mix? Let $p$ be the cost of one pound of peanuts and $w$ be the cost of one pound of walnuts. For the trail mix, the cost according to the given amounts is: $$2.10 = \frac{p}{2} + \frac{w}{3} + \frac{0.17}{\text{lb}} \cdot \left(\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3}\right)$$ And for the other scenario: $$1.80 = \frac{p}{3} + \frac{w}{2} - 0.17 \text{ (since additives are not present here)}$$ So we have two equations: \begin{align*}
2.10 & = \frac{p}{2} + \frac{w}{3} + 0.17, \\
1.80 & = \frac{p}{3} + \frac{w}{2}.
\end{align*} Solving these as before, we get $14$ cents for a one-pound bag of walnuts.

Daniel works for a sports stadium filling water bottles for athletes. He filled 254 water bottles this season. The football team had 11 players that wanted 6 bottles each. The soccer team had him fill 53 bottles. The lacrosse team needed 12 more bottles than the football team. Each team coach during the season also wanted two bottles apiece. How many bottles did he fill for the rugby team during the final game he worked this season? The football team requested 11 players * 6 bottles = 66 bottles.
The lacrosse team requested 66 + 12 bottles = 78 bottles.
The team coaches requested 2 bottles * 4 teams = 8 total bottles.
In total, he filled 66 + 53 + 78 + 8 bottles = 205 bottles for all teams and coaches.
He filled 254 total bottles – 205 filled for other teams and coaches = 49 bottles for the rugby team.

