If the radius of a sphere is p units and the radius of a hemisphere is 2p units, what is the ratio of the volume of the sphere to the volume of the hemisphere?
The volume of a sphere with radius $r$ is $\frac{4}{3}\pi r^3$,
and the volume of a hemisphere with radius $r$ is $\frac{2}{3}\pi r^3$.
So, for the given values of $p$, the ratio of the volume of the sphere to the volume of the hemisphere is $\frac{\frac{4}{3}\pi p^3}{\frac{2}{3}\pi (2p)^3}=\frac{\frac{4}{3}\pi p^3}{\frac{16}{3}\pi p^3}=\frac{4}{16}=\boxed{\frac{1}{4}}$.",67.46995052501315,20.921551244410086
