A particle moves so that it is at $(2t + 7, 4t - 13)$ at time $t.$  Find the speed of the particle, measured in unit of distance per unit of time. The distance between two points $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$ is given by the distance formula $d = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}$.

At time $t$, the particle is at $(2t + 7, 4t - 13)$. At time $t + dt$, the particle is at $(2(t + dt) + 7, 4(t + dt) - 13)$.

The change in the $x$-coordinate is $2(t + dt) + 7 - (2t + 7) = 2dt$, and the change in the $y$-coordinate is $4(t + dt) - 13 - (4t - 13) = 4dt$.

So the speed of the particle, which is the magnitude of the velocity vector, is given by

$$\sqrt{(2dt)^2 + (4dt)^2} = \sqrt{4dt^2 + 16dt^2} = \sqrt{20dt^2} = \sqrt{20} dt.$$

Therefore, the speed of the particle is $\sqrt{20}$ units of distance per unit of time. To summarize, our answer is \boxed{\sqrt{20}}

