# A New Sorting Algorithm

Category:
Computing

Patrick Hamlyn

Peter Fey

Version:
24 02 2001

I saw an interesting article on Kolosov Sorting in a book by O'Reilly, Algorithm Design Secrets. It inspired me to come up with my own algorithm, a more efficient sorting that still only depends on comparison operations. The algorithm makes only about n log(n) passes and n exchanges, compared to the famous Merge Sort algorithm which makes 2 passes over each sublist, of n elements, for a total of about n log(n) passes. (The algorithm coded in Java below makes exactly n log(n) passes, but the implementation I have coded does 2 exchanges per pass, rather than 0.5 exchanges per pass as in the Merge Sort.)

## Starting Point

The main idea is to split the input list up into smaller and smaller sublists, progressively sorting them in the process and increasing their number of elements, until the entire list is sorted.

Here is a sketch example (see screen captures below) of first sorting the elements of a copy of the list and then sorting the result:

• sort all 4 elements

• sort another 4 elements

• sort the 4th and 5th elements together

• sort the 6th, 7th, 8th and 9th elements

• sort the 10th and 11th elements together

• sort the 12th, 13th, 14th and 15th elements

• sort the 2nd, 3rd and 5th elements together

• sort the 21st and 22nd elements together

• sort the 23rd and 24th elements together

Obviously by sorting the ends of each sublist first and then sorting what remains the whole thing will be done.

## The Algorithm

The algorithm is a ""fast sort"" and makes no assumptions about the input list. It does not depend on any key produced by comparing elements of the list, nor does it depend on counting number of occurances of elements. It can be applied to the shortest of an alphabet list. The algorithm inspects pairs of elements until the whole list has been sorted, and relies on comparing elements to both extend the list to be sorted and also to sort it.

As with the Merge Sort, where intermediate collecitons in two temporary arrays are recombined into a single sorted two sublist, so this algorithm progressively does sortings on smaller and smaller sublists, until the whole list has been sorted. When a sublist of size n is found, five things must happen:

• the last element of this sublist is copied out of the unsorted part

• this last element is added to the sorted end of the large list

• this sublist (now",10.666163380465875,4.493473705744843
