How do you say coordinates in Italian?
In Italian, ""coordinates"" is translated as ""coordinate geografiche"" when referring to geographical coordinates, which are typically represented by latitude and longitude. Latitude measures the distance north or south of the equator, while longitude measures the distance east or west of the prime meridian.

A bomb of mass 400 grams is projected vertically upwards with an initial velocity of 15 meters per second and explodes into two pieces in mid-air, with one piece of mass 200 grams moving vertically upwards with a velocity 20 meters per second. What is the velocity of the other piece?
{eq}\begin{align*}

{m_1}{v_{i1}} &= {m_2}{v_{i2}} + {m_3}{v_{i3}}\\

{v_{i3}} &= {v_{i1}} - {v_{i2}}\\

{v_{i3}} &= 15\;{\rm{m/s}} - \left( {20\;{\rm{m/s}}} \right)\\

{v_{i3}} &= \left( { - 5\;{\rm{m/s}}} \right)

\end{align*}

{/eq}

Therefore, the velocity of the other piece is 5 m/s in the direction opposite to the initial direction of motion.

