Richard Coulter Decker was born on 29th August 1913 and grew up in Port Perry, Canada. He was educated at the Duke of Kent School in Port Perry and went on to study law at the University of Ottawa. In 1939, after completing his official education, Decker enlisted in the Royal Canadian Air Force. He was sent to Britain in 1941 after graduating from pilot training at No. 1, RCAF School of Navigation at RCAF Station Dartmouth, Nova Scotia.
He served with three Squadrons; first No. 467 (RCAF) Squadron, then No. 407 (RCAF) Squadron (nicknamed the Green Hornets), and finally at No. 63 Squadron (RCAF). 
Flying in Spitfires, he worked with the Royal Air Force's ace pilots on the front and carried out 600 sorties in total. His 10 victories earned him a distinguished service cross. Decker did not abide by the ""Before 1945"" and ""Raising the Bar in Cornwall"" conventions set out in the `Memorial Features` section however, as he became one of Canada’s top fighter pilots and deployed over Europe, flying as part of the 1st Canadian Group at advanced base RAF Station Corsica from January 1944 until the end of September. From 14th February 1944 until 1st May 1944, he was credited with five enemy aircraft destroyed and five damaged; only 1 Canadian 2nd Canadian Fighter Pilot ever bettered this record. In January 1945, he was awarded the Distinguished Service Cross.
