I have bumbled from one thing to another when I've attempted to outline Lyndon's own reactions to history: Was he an objective or a subjective historian?  Was he more interested in the results of history than its causes? Did he see history as a drama unfolding, or a set of static figures in situ?
When Ed sat down with Lyndon, we were in the sitting room on the upper floor of his Capitol Hill townhouse.  When Lyndon found useful, adding advantageous detail and perspective to stories about relationships, he would tell his staff to retrieve him the figures he had jotted down earlier. These were often found at the bottom of pages of his novel that he was working on. When it was time to have supper, we all retired to a back dining room in which simultaneously Lyndon and Ed were working the phones talking about their plans and necessities of the coming campaign. ""We had dinner at our house a few times,"" Ed says, ""and he was much gay and quite enjoyable...I found him to be very revealing about his feelings about election night of 1948. Rhode Island having been taken out of the race, I don't believe there was anyone except Jesse-Jeff Westwood and Lyndon who was certain he'd get the nomination. He said in very wellPut phrases, 'When they told me that I was going to be the nominee, but that the delegates could try to steal it away, and I told these delegates that if they tried to steal it away, they bloody well had better damn near kill me in the process of doing so.'""
In another time and place, the sudden crackle of the effects of his anger and disgust made him all the more interesting; the threats made more vivid, therefore, the money he would be able to raise from those who would be frightened enough to give it to him. But in Ohio in 1960, it was not possible to count on those proven champions—Chiles and the Averys of Ohio—having the needed resources and could be counted upon at least to work wholeheartedly for him in a manner that would ensure his nomination.",25.285255084482426,34.06537238147564
