In the world we live in, there is a lot of talk about life satisfaction. Individually, in a relatively short period of time we all build up a whole mental list of things we hope to achieve and experiences we’d like to have. We dream of our “prosperous futures”, we fantasize about what life would be like when we’re happily settled. Generally, the idea itself works pretty well, allowing us to focus our goals and stay on track. But the problem comes in when we let the ‘prosperous future’ become a replacement for actually leading a life worth living in the present.
While we spend years molding and preparing the idea of a life ahead of us, cultivating this faraway, idyllic checkpoint, do we ever stop and ask ourselves; ‘where does that “certain important feeling” compute into our life today? Today, how do we feel? Today, what matters most to us? Are we actually living the life we deserve? Are we allowing our pain to win over our dreams?
 The fact of the matter is, the majority of people do not have the luxury of living life the way they want to – and acknowledging this is your first step in improving the quality of life you lead.
We are happiest, most productive, and, by extension, most successful when our core needs are met. According to Maslow’s hierarchy of needs, we can get these needs met in many different ways, but they remain the same.
