In some cultures the average woman has expectations to behave modestly (e.g. by covering up partially or maybe completely), be identified as a wife and/or mother, and when a woman is active in the market economy, she does it as an exception. Example: In the majority of the western world there is the notion that the so-called man-cares for the family while the woman works outside (e.g. in the market economy). In contrast to this, in some societies the roles and responsibilities of men and women are more clearly and equal, for example, when it comes to education, professional trainings or getting jobs. 
In most cultures, it is thought that men should be courageous, influential, passionate, assertive, brave, clear-minded, logical, open-minded, etc. While women are expected to be gentle, intelligent, well-behaved, caring, sensitive, responsible, competent, etc.
Of course, these are generalizations, and individual perspectives can vary widely from person to person. Taken together they tell us, however, that different cultures, societies, and even individuals, have different beliefs surrounding gender roles. Cultural beliefs largely dictate where the divide between feminine and masculine roles lies as well as what manner of social conformity or impermissibility of transgressions define them. The values and expectations attached to each gender role vary widely among different societies; what is a harsh critique of one society could be celebrated as a type of progress in another.
You can use this information to form your own opinions on gender roles, however, I'd like to remind you that these are generalizations, not hard facts. As much as we like to divide the world into man/woman, masculine/feminine, male/female – the real world is much more diverse and complex.
