 John draws a regular five pointed star in the sand, and at each of the 5 outward-pointing points and 5 inward-pointing points he places one of ten different sea shells. How many ways can he place the shells, if reflections and rotations of an arrangement are considered equivalent? If we label the points of the star from 1 to 5, clockwise, we can distinctively place the shells by placing them in order at 1-5-12-13-14-15 positions.  From here, 10 distinct shell choices can be made for position number 1, 9 choices for position number 2, and so on.  Now by having 10 choices for 5 positions and 9 choices for the next 4 positions given those choices, ordering becomes distinct.  Thus the solution is
$$10\cdot9\cdot8\cdot7\cdot6\cdot5 = \boxed{151\,200}$$
Note that in the above solution, swapping two shells in the first and second positions would create an equivalent arrangement, because rotations and reflections are considered equivalent.  If the problem did not count arrangements as equivalent, we could simply multiply our answer by $20$ to account for the 20 possible rotations and reflections.
The answer is: 151,200 
