Trust him and hold him accountable.

Regardless of your stance on whether or not your husband should revisit his affair, what is most most important is trust. Unfortunately, people, including married folk, are often untrustworthy.
After cheating, most folk will do anything to preserve their relationship, and this can lead a person to deny things that they really do. They've been “hurt” before, they’re afraid of being alone or they’re just naturally untrustworthy.
Remind yourself that he is making the relationship work, and hold him accountable for his behavior. Depending on how much you do trust him, this might be as simple as agreeing to make all major financial decisions together or asking which specific aspects of his life you, as his wife, should have access to. Or it might be as big a step as guaranteeing all future monies go directly into a joint bank account and that you both have the ability to read each other’s private messages (depending on the severity of his betrayal).
General trust can be decided within the relationship. Partnering only pays off in the long term if people maintain trust and build stability. But when that trust is broken due to something like infidelity, you’ll get a more accurate sense of where regularity, partnership and compromise can exist going forward.
If maintaining trust with your husband going forward is essential to your life, working through this betrayal won’t be an easy challenge, but it might be worth it.
That being said, it is your life. Don’t feel that a relationship is something that requires a certain compromise or recalibration. It is your right to hold your husband accountable. Let your communication guide your decisions, and do not feel prosecuting your husband would lack integrity. Communication is always a two way street. Abuse isn’t born on one side of the equation; both parties can influence how it takes place. If your husband is not accountable in the relationship, that opens the relationship up to a whole new set of dynamics, and unfortunately that includes you as his partner.
