Sunfish grow up to 20–24 inches in length, and are bottom dwellers that prefer clear water, small streams, and places with plants or objects to shelter in. ""Centrarchus"" and ""Astyanax"" are the genera of sunfish. Centrarchids are fairly athletic fish, capable of growing large and moving quickly even in relatively spacious home aquaria. They spawn nearly year round and are fairly easy to breed by entrance disadvantages to the home aquarist. One of the most well known of the sunfish is the bluegill, ""Centrarchus micropterus.

The sunfish consists of various largemouth and smallmouth bass, bluegill, shellcracker, bowfin, yellow perch and others. Sunfish are difficult to identify, because they have so many subspecies and because many of the subspecies and species don't look very different, so care must be taken when identifying sunfish.

